Date: Thu 6 Aug 2015
Source: North Wales Chronicle UK [edited]
http://www.northwaleschronicle.co.uk/news/151120/leading-bangor-conservationist-left-in-coma-by-mosquito-bite-is-flown-back-to-uk.aspx


A leading conservationist who was left in critical condition with a viral brain infection after a mosquito bite has been flown back to the UK. Highly-respected conservationist Sophie Williams, who lectures at Bangor University [Gwynedd County, North Wales], was left in a coma after she was infected with Japanese encephalitis while working in China in July [2015]. The 31-year-old, of Yorkshire [England], was on a research trip in Asia when she contracted the virus, which is spread through mosquito bites, and was treated in a Bangkok [Thailand] hospital before flying back home this weekend [1-2 Aug 2015].

A spokesman for Bangor University said: "Dr Sophie Williams, a lecturer in Conservation Science at Bangor University fell ill during a visit to China. Sophie, a highly-respected and well liked conservation expert, was working on the joint project between Xishuangbanna Tropical Botanic Garden [Mengla County, Xishuangbanna Dai Autonomous Prefecture, Yunnan province, China] and Bangor University's Treborth Botanic Garden when she was taken ill. "After initial assessment and treatment, she was transferred to another hospital in Bangkok and then flown back to the UK over the weekend [1-2 Aug 2015]." Dr Williams' father Mike, owner of Castlegate News in Yorkshire, said family and friends were facing a nervous wait...

Japanese encephalitis is common in rural areas of South East Asia and the Pacific islands and the Far East, but is rare in travellers. There is no cure for the disease so treatment is focused on relieving clinical symptoms and supporting the patient to overcome the infection. The virus is found in pigs and birds, and is passed to mosquitoes that bite the infected animals and cannot be spread from person to person. The Bangor University spokesperson added: "The staff of Xishuangbanna Tropical Botanic Garden as well as the health-care staff at the hospitals in Xishuangbanna and Bangkok have provided excellent care and support for Sophie and her family. In addition, the staff of the British Embassy and the insurance company have provided invaluable assistance. "We wish Sophie a rapid recovery."

[Byline: Mike Williams]

